\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:orge6c97b9}
Table 1 shows how a smaller resistor value (bigger load) increases the ripple voltage. Since \(\tau = R \cdot C\) we know this is because the capacitor will discharge faster with a smaller resistance value, hence, the voltage will drop lower in the discharge time. Using a larger capacitor value reduces this ripple similarly, as the value of C in increased. By looking at the V\(_{\text{Avg}}\) values we can also deduce that a smaller ripple voltage leads to a higher average voltage. This makes sense as the voltage is kept at a higher level.\newline\newline
As the line voltage to the primary coil of the transformer is altered, the voltage at the secondary coil reduces or increases proportionally. The average voltage and ripple voltage also reduce or increase together with line voltage. This is an undesired result as the device being powered by our power supply might not be able to take 10 or 15V, but only 12-13V, and mains voltage can be unpredictable at times.\newline\newline
Adding the 5V regulator to the circuit demonstrated how the output voltage can be kept very constant. At input voltages above 6.56V, the output voltage was a steady 4.99V DC with ripple voltage that was indistinguishable from noise on the oscilloscope. Below this voltage, however, not enough voltage is supplied to the regulator and the output voltage begins to drop and the familiar ripple voltage from the unregulated power supply can be seen.
